	abstract = {Abstract
            
              We theoretically investigate transmissive Goos–Hänchen ({TGH}) shifts supported by defect resonances in a one-dimensional photonic crystal containing an isotropic chiral defect layer. The defect mode provides strong intracavity localization and a sharply dispersive transmission phase, while chirality introduces polarization coupling and helicity-dependent phase accumulation that reshapes the resonance dispersion. As a result, the angular derivative of the transmission phase becomes strongly enhanced near the defect resonance, yielding giant lateral displacements of the transmitted beam. For a baseline cavity with moderate Bragg mirrors (e.g.,
              N
              = 8), the normalized shift reaches the order of 10
              2
              , whereas increasing the mirror periods and tuning the incidence angle can further boost the shift to exceed 10
