              bi[13]
              ) formed, joining two helicenes with the same helicity in their keto tautomeric forms. Using Cu
              {II}
              ({OTf})₂ as the oxidant led to an unsymmetrical [27]helicenoid composed by an (
              M
              )‐ and a (
              P
              )‐enantiomer of the [13]helicene through an unusual coupling between the 1‐ and 3‐positions of the 2‐naphthol units. Structural characterization was achieved by {NMR} spectroscopy and single‐crystal (X‐ray or electron) diffraction analysis. The enantiomers of this
              [27]helicenoid
              were analyzed by electronic circular dichroism ({ECD}) and {CPL} measurements. The spectroscopic data were corroborated by {DFT} calculations, and the intense {CPL} output is preserved despite the presence of an (
              M
              )‐
              and a
              (
              
                P
              
